<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06048120 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06048120 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  CHILDREN; FAMILY; SANTA-CLARA; COUNTY; SERVICE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The Santa Clara County Social Services Agency is conducting its secondrecruitment campaign for black foster and adoptive parents. The campaign beganFeb. 1 and will run through April 30.;    Targeted recruitment is needed dueto the large number of minority children in out-of-home care in Santa ClaraCounty. Of the more than 2,700 children in out-of-home placement in SantaClara county, 18 percent are black. The total black population in Santa ClaraCounty is 3 percent.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  KIDS WHO WAIT  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The Social Service Agency tries to keep children with their family wheneverpossible. But if children need to be removed for their own safety, it ispreferable to place them with a family of similar ethnic and culturalbackground.;    There will be a kickoff event on Saturday at Antioch Baptist,268 E. Julian St., San Jose, from 3 until 5 p.m.;    For more information onbecoming a foster or adoptive parent, or to become involved in the campaign,call the Santa Clara County Recruitment Unit at (408) 299-KIDS.  </TEXT><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910217  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Sunday  </DAY><MONTH>  February  </MONTH><PG.COL>  7B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  170  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Sunday February 17, 199100048120,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>